pathæ˜¯å®é™…å—æ§åˆ¶å™¨å½±å“çš„çŠ¶æ€é‡ï¼Œä¸ºï¼ˆç«–ç›´æ–¹å‘ä½ç½®å’Œé€Ÿåº¦ï¼‰ã€‚flapæ˜¯æ§åˆ¶é‡ï¼Œåœ¨æ¯ä¸ªæ—¶é—´ç‚¹æ˜¯å¦å‘ä¸Šé£ã€‚ç³»ç»Ÿæ¨¡å‹
PIPEGAPSIZE  = 100 # gap between upper and lower pipe
PIPEWIDTH = 52
BIRDWIDTH = 34
BIRDHEIGHT = 24
BIRDDIAMETER = np.sqrt(BIRDHEIGHT**2 + BIRDWIDTH**2) # the bird rotates in the game, so we use it&#039;s maximum extent
ä¸Šä¸‹ç®¡é“ä¹‹é—´çš„è·ç¦»ï¼Œç®¡é“å®½åº¦å‡ä¸ºå¸¸æ•°
def solve(playery, playerVelY, lowerPipes):
    pipeVelX = -4 # speed in x
    playerAccY    =   1   # players downward accleration
    playerFlapAcc =  -14   # players speed on flapping
å› ä¸ºé¸Ÿä¸ç®¡é“æ˜¯ç›¸å¯¹è¿åŠ¨ï¼Œæ‰€ä»¥pipeVelXä¹Ÿå°±æ˜¯é¸Ÿå‰è¿›çš„é€Ÿåº¦ï¼ˆå¸¸æ•°ï¼‰
lowerpipes: ä¸‹æ–¹ç®¡é“çš„ä¸Šç•Œï¼ˆä¸‹æ–¹çº¢è‰²åå­—ï¼‰ï¼Œå› ä¸ºä¸Šä¸‹ç®¡é“è·ç¦»ä¸ºå¸¸æ•°æ‰€ä»¥ä¸Šæ–¹ç®¡é“ä½ç½®ï¼ˆè“åå­—ï¼‰ä¹Ÿå·²çŸ¥

y = path[:,0]
vy = path[:,1]

c = [] # init constraint list
c += [y &lt;= GROUND, y &gt;= SKY] # constraints for sky and ground
c += [y[0] == playery, vy[0] == playerVelY] # initial conditions
æ™®é€‚çš„contstraintsåŒ…æ‹¬ï¼šé¸Ÿä¸èƒ½è¶Šè¿‡ä¸Šä¸‹è¾¹ç•Œï¼ŒåŠæ—¶åˆ»çš„ä½ç½®å’Œé€Ÿåº¦ï¼ˆç»™å®šï¼‰
 for t in range(N-1): # look ahead
    dt = t//15 + 1 # let time get coarser further in the look ahead
    x -= dt * pipeVelX # update x
    xs += [x] # add to list
    c += [vy[t + 1] ==  vy[t] + playerAccY * dt + playerFlapAcc * flap[t] ] # add y velocity constraint, f=ma
    c += [y[t + 1] ==  y[t] + vy[t + 1]*dt ] # add y constraint, dy/dt = a
    pipe_c, dist = getPipeConstraintsDistance(x, y[t+1], lowerPipes) # add pipe constraints
    c += pipe_c
    obj += dist
å‰é¢çš„dtè¾ƒå°ï¼Œåé¢çš„dtè¾ƒå¤§ã€‚åœ¨å‰é¢è¿›è¡Œç›¸å¯¹å¯†é›†çš„é‡‡æ ·ä¿æŒä¼°è®¡çš„ç²¾åº¦ï¼Œåé¢é™ä½é‡‡æ ·ç‡æ‰©å±•æ•´ä¸ªä¼°è®¡çš„é•¿åº¦ï¼Œä½œè€…åœ¨blogé‡Œè¿›è¡Œäº†è§£é‡Šã€‚

This technique works pretty well. It doesnâ€™t quite run in real time with the lookahead set to a distance that allows it to succeed. We used a neat trick to improve the speed and look ahead distance. The modelâ€™s time step increases with look ahead time. In other words, the model is precise for its first few time steps, and gets less careful later in its prediction. The thinking is that this allows it to make approximate long term plans about jump timing without over-taxing the solver.

ä¸ºåŒ€é€Ÿï¼Œç”±ä¸Šä¸€æ—¶åˆ»çš„ï¼Œé‡åŠ›ï¼ŒåŠæ˜¯å¦å‘ä¸Šé£å†³å®šï¼ˆä¸å¤ªç¡®å®šä¸ºä»€ä¹ˆplayerFlapAccæ²¡æœ‰ä¹˜ä»¥dtï¼Œä½†æ˜¯æµ‹è¯•æ—¶å‘ç°å¦‚æœä¹˜äº†çš„è¯æ•ˆæœä¸å¥½ï¼‰ã€‚ã€‚è¿™äº›å‡ä»¥constraintsçš„å½¢å¼è¡¨ç¤ºï¼ˆä¼˜åŒ–æ—¶éœ€è¦å…ˆæ»¡è¶³/è®¡ç®—è¿™äº›å‚æ•°ï¼‰
def getPipeConstraintsDistance(x, y, lowerPipes):
    constraints = [] # init pipe constraint list
    pipe_dist = 0 # init dist from pipe center
    for pipe in lowerPipes:
        dist_from_front = pipe[&#039;x&#039;] - x - BIRDDIAMETER
        dist_from_back = pipe[&#039;x&#039;] - x + PIPEWIDTH
        if (dist_from_front &lt; 0) and (dist_from_back &gt; 0):
            constraints += [y &lt;= (pipe[&#039;y&#039;] - BIRDDIAMETER)] # y above lower pipe
            constraints += [y &gt;= (pipe[&#039;y&#039;] - PIPEGAPSIZE)] # y below upper pipe
            pipe_dist += cvx.abs(pipe[&#039;y&#039;] - (PIPEGAPSIZE//2) - (BIRDDIAMETER//2) - y) # add distance from center
    return constraints, pipe_dist
